The paper deals with source coding problems with security constraints, which are typically studied in the information theory community. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves eavesdropping and secrecy, which are common topics in the cryptography community, making cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another likely sub-category. The paper also involves the use of private links and the study of tradeoffs, which are common topics in the multimedia community, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category. The paper also involves the study of optimal rate-distortion-equivocation tradeoffs, which is a topic in the signal processing community, making cs.SI (Signal Processing) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the study of networks and connections with secret-sharing and encryption, which are topics in the distributed systems community, making cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) a possible sub-category.
